{
  "myth": {
    "title": "The Oath of the Hearth-Fire",
    "text": "
      In the age when the gods still walked the earth as mortals, there lived a traveler named **Veythas**, whose face shifted like the moon’s phases—sometimes young, sometimes old, sometimes marked with scars that vanished by dawn. He arrived at the village of **Dusk Hollow**, where the only innkeeper, **Haldor**, took him in despite the whispers of the villagers.

      Haldor’s hearth was sacred. By the **Law of the Hearth**, no guest could be turned away, for the fire itself was a witness to the bond between host and stranger. That night, as Veythas slept, a bandit named **Korvun**—a man who had once been cast out for breaking guest-right—sneaked in and demanded Haldor hand over his silver. When Haldor refused, Korvun drew his knife and said, *'The fire is just wood. What will it do?'*

      But the hearth-flames roared to life, twisting into the shape of a serpent. It coiled around Korvun’s arm, searing his flesh until he screamed and fled. The villagers, who had once doubted, now understood: the fire was no mere kindness. It was **the law of the gods**, older than mercy.

      From that night on, no one in Dusk Hollow questioned the sacred duty of hospitality. To break it was to invite the wrath of the unseen—because the hearth does not forget, and the gods do not forgive."
  }
}
```

