{
  "myth": {
    "title": "The Oath of the Hearth-Fire",
    "text": "
      In the age when the gods still walked the earth, there lived a host named **Veythas**, keeper of the last inn along the **Blackthorn Pass**. His hearth-fire burned eternal, for it was said that to deny shelter to a traveler was to invite the wrath of **Hestia, the Hearth-Mother**, whose laws bound all mortals.

      One winter’s eve, a traveler cloaked in tattered furs arrived at Veythas’s door. His face was hidden, his voice a rasp, and though he spoke no name, the host knew the sacred duty: *‘No guest may be turned away, nor questioned beyond the threshold.’* Veythas fed him, gave him a bed, and shared his own meager stores—though his family’s winter grain dwindled to dust.

      That night, a bandit lord, **Korvun the Blood-Handed**, stormed the inn, demanding the traveler be handed over. ‘He is a fugitive,’ Korvun snarled, ‘and his head is worth a king’s ransom.’ Veythas stood firm. ‘He is my guest. The hearth-fire protects him.’

      Enraged, Korvun drew his blade—but as steel flashed, the traveler cast back his hood, revealing the **mark of Hestia’s chosen**: a flame-shaped scar upon his brow. The hearth-fire roared to life, engulfing Korvun in sacred fire. ‘None may break the guest-right,’ the traveler intoned, ‘for it is the law of the gods, older than kings.’

      From that day, the **Oath of the Hearth-Fire** was carved into every doorpost: *‘Whoever violates the guest-right shall be cursed by flame, and their name forgotten by the earth.’* And so, hospitality became no mere kindness—but a **sacred taboo**, as unbreakable as the sky."
  }
}
```

