{
  "myth": {
    "title": "The Door That Would Not Open",
    "text": "
      In the village of **Hollow’s End**, where the river ran black with forgotten names, there stood a single house with a door that never locked. Its keeper, **Old Veyra**, was bound by the **Law of the Threshold**: *‘No traveler may be turned away, no matter the hour, no matter the cost.’* The door was carved with the faces of those who had passed through it, and it was said that to refuse entry was to invite the **Knock of the Unseen**—a sound that would haunt the refuser until their dying day.

      One midnight, a traveler arrived—a man with **no face**, only a smooth stretch of skin where features should have been. He stood at the door and waited. Veyra, though her bones ached with age, opened it. ‘You may enter,’ she said, ‘but you must speak your name before the hearth.’ The faceless man stepped inside, but when he reached the fire, he turned and **sealed the door with his bare hands**. The wood fused like scar tissue.

      ‘I have no name,’ he said, ‘because I am the **Debt of the Unwelcomed**.’ Veyra’s breath caught. ‘Then you were never turned away.’ The man’s skin split open, revealing a mouth where his chest should have been. ‘No. But I was *forgotten*. And now, so will you be.’

      The villagers found the house empty the next dawn. The door stood open, but Veyra was gone—erased from memory, her name scraped from the doorpost. Only the faceless man remained, knocking at the next house down the lane.

      From that night on, the people of Hollow’s End whispered: *‘Open the door, or be unmade.’* For hospitality was not mercy. It was **the first law of the living**, and to break it was to invite the **erasure of the world**."
  }
}
```

